045C476224964BDEA9BD119B7E346C33.description: The fundamental source of all energy in the universe is the conversion of mass into energy.*

3487DAD3B7134741AD9ABA25D4A8BBBC.description: The total of the fundamental interactions is responsible for the appearance and behavior of the objects in the universe.

CBD462AF7DE24C12AFDEA9D16084A6E5.description: Behaviors and characteristics of matter, from the microscopic to the cosmic levels, are manifestations of its atomic structure. The macroscopic characteristics of matter, such as electrical and optical properties, are the result of microscopic interactions.

04046764426E4D5AA9384E61A07CCD58.description: The Standard Model of Particle Physics has evolved from previous attempts to explain the nature of the atom and states that: • atomic particles are composed of subnuclear particles • the nucleus is a comglomeration of quarks which manifest themselves as protons and neutrons • each elementary particle has a corresponding antiparticle

5021860F55D24B1B88605FA3DFDE1C1F.description: Among other things, mass-energy and charge are conserved at all levels (from subnuclear to cosmic).

3E992F34BC144C0FAAF31FB949B2AC26.description: On the atomic level, energy and matter exhibit the characteristics of both waves and particles.

4954B9D00079463A9D8E5D2F660B7DB5.description: The energy of a photon is proportional to its frequency.*

103138E6C18649E5B5E0413E45FDE199.description: On the atomic level, energy is emitted or absorbed in discrete packets called photons.*

A79A1A612BFB4F5AA613302E6A08162F.description: Charge is quantized on two levels. On the atomic level, charge is restricted to multiples of the elementary charge (charge on the electron or proton). On the subnuclear level, charge appears as fractional values of the elementary charge (quarks).

E5310EC207814D118198D6723CD4BBEB.description: States of matter and energy are restricted to discrete values (quantized).

6F90E83B97934F1A9197C8A708DC2C16.description:
Performance Indicator 5.3: Students can compare energy relationships within an atom’s nucleus to those outside the
nucleus.

A37A473F15944C499B7C5530D00D2EC3.description: The inverse square law applies to electrical* and gravitational* fields produced by point sources.

4206B13A87774096AD131B6E490F76D2.description: Gravitational forces are only attractive, whereas electrical and magnetic forces can be attractive or repulsive.

5BC4CE7195D0499DA5B15EC7D1E3E2F3.description: Field strength* and direction are determined using a suitable test particle.

5CC4A39A6A8A402584A5EF8FDAD13CC7.description: Momentum is conserved in a closed system.*

30CAFD76977342E1B845EB0E40883998.description: According to Newton’s Third Law, forces occur in action/reaction pairs. When one object exerts a force on a second, the second exerts a force on the first that is equal in magnitude and opposite in direction

E028CBF9F57D4B789E8F3C58147F16FC.description: The impulse* imparted to an object causes a change in its momentum*.

936226FF4CDF4198A1029E46D71CCF53.description: Kinetic friction* is a force that opposes motion.

F0FD2DE2FF93437A89CAA0E5878CBF02.description: Centripetal force* is the net force which produces centripetal acceleration.* In uniform circular motion, the centripetal force is perpendicular to the tangential velocity.

90155EA45BF24EE9B9BDD02C95B44FE7.description: The elongation or compression of a spring depends upon the nature of the spring (its spring constant) and the magnitude of the applied force.*

37D7FB087F5945E285913F70ED14D5D6.description: Weight is the gravitational force with which a planet attracts a mass*. The mass of an object is independent of the gravitational field in which it is located.

1F145EF6157E44FCA371FE76E781B91C.description: According to Newton’s Second Law, an unbalanced force causes a mass to accelerate*.

2891F92ABACA48BEAB46F262FCE8F24E.description: When the net force on a system is zero, the system is in equilibrium.

AE364D9CDA04498B8ABFACE0DACA770B.description: According to Newton’s First Law, the inertia of an object is directly proportional to its mass. An object remains at rest or moves with constant velocity, unless acted upon by an unbalanced force.

E0008BF5B60D400BBCF27BA5F8EF556C.description: The horizontal displacement of a projectile is dependent upon the horizontal component of its motion and its time of flight.

5DFC77561DA84A1CAB03B7DC7DA4A0FA.description: A projectile’s time of flight is dependent upon the vertical component of its motion.

ABEDFD400055496D889F803214E03F9B.description: The path of a projectile is the result of the simultaneous effect of the horizontal and vertical components of its motion; these components act independently.

08DB4C52A90D431E88FBC9AAC3D2DF77.description: An object in free fall accelerates due to the force of gravity.* Friction and other forces cause the actual motion of a falling object to deviate from its theoretical motion.

3DC281275F5B418C9F2C8EE6B030D3C4.description: An object in linear motion may travel with a constant velocity* or with acceleration*.

DB2BA4CD4E4042988E64DBABAEB77FD3.description: The resultant of two or more vectors, acting at any angle, is determined by vector addition.

A4329E4F599647C990FB77995A928A13.description: A vector may be resolved into perpendicular components.*

A4ED7CCFF5FD45FD8B084E40273E6F58.description: Measured quantities can be classified as either vector or scalar.

A68905CB3B384816B32E00E4C9431B7E.description:
Performance Indicator 5.1: Students can explain and predict different patterns of motion of objects (e.g., linear and uniform
circular motion, velocity and acceleration, momentum and inertia).

BB3F3ABFAFB848BE98CC7F46156AA0B8.description: When a wave source and an observer are in relative motion, the observed frequency of the waves traveling between them is shifted (Doppler effect).

C9F6E105D6594E98A5A76F2162709F00.description: When waves of a similar nature meet, the resulting interference may be explained using the principle of superposition. Standing waves are a special case of interference.

FE763412F78542BF93386AF2AF21AE0B.description: Diffraction occurs when waves pass by obstacles or through openings. The wavelength of the incident wave and the size of the obstacle or opening affect how the wave spreads out.

85D3A431964E4289AE67C25424DC7BD5.description: All frequencies of electromagnetic radiation travel at the same speed in a vacuum.*

4FA386C2F0224B4CB1468A847F47AD1E.description: The absolute index of refraction is inversely proportional to the speed of a wave.*

87719444C6104C60B427854EDEF43FCE.description: When a wave moves from one medium into another, the wave may refract due to a change in speed. The angle of refraction (measured with respect to the normal) depends on the angle of incidence and the properties of the media (indices of refraction).*

61BB06439314472495B3294917DFA35F.description: When a wave strikes a boundary between two media, reflection*, transmission, and absorption occur. A transmitted wave may be refracted.

B3BBB0C053974E9CB8AE0A595DF0A286.description: Electromagnetic radiation exhibits wave characteristics. Electromagnetic waves can propagate through a vacuum.

DE3C3E604E834A12AC50C2EAEDD8299A.description: Resonance occurs when energy is transferred to a system at its natural frequency.

4A46C40CA3884F1ABFDA8C816BFEC0C2.description: Waves are categorized by the direction in which particles in a medium vibrate about an equilibrium position relative to the direction of propagation of the wave, such as transverse and longitudinal waves.

0205A5EC37784B32A5AEF17E7BEFB307.description: Mechanical waves require a material medium through which to travel.

A3D31D7B10304A59BADE6C7B0E49DFE8.description: The model of a wave incorporates the characteristics of amplitude, wavelength,* frequency*, period*, wave speed*, and phase.

DD7B5BD413A84D5EBEF809FF55BA01FA.description: Waves carry energy and information without transferring mass. This energy may be carried by pulses or periodic waves.

29BCED93B14247AE81B562BF9FA01512.description: An oscillating system produces waves. The nature of the system determines the type of wave produced.

55D3EBCA856844B3B68A17684F0A1467.description:
Performance Indicator 4.3: Students can explain variations in wavelength and frequency in terms of the source of the
vibrations that produce them, e.g., molecules, electrons, and nuclear particles.

6D591344138D444DA76CBDE45A390752.description: Electrical power* and energy* can be determined for electric circuits.

C3A87B2B8CF14FB7AB1826A402F59F69.description: Circuit components may be connected in series* or in parallel*. Schematic diagrams are used to represent circuits and circuit elements.

CAC0D4051E0143409CB222F95D4453B4.description: A circuit is a closed path in which a current* can exist. (Note: Use conventional current.)

F412FEBF37414E028E7031D8B9856CD1.description: The factors affecting resistance in a conductor are length, cross-sectional area, temperature, and resistivity.*

A101105CA856415E9076FB23EBF7442E.description: All materials display a range of conductivity. At constant temperature, common metallic conductors obey Ohm’s Law*.

83CA97884BF844D19D68AD33B701D7C3.description: Moving electric charges produce magnetic fields. The relative motion between a conductor and a magnetic field may produce a potential difference in the conductor.

96D5BB990CF44EF89EFD72F35E5E619C.description: Energy may be stored in electric* or magnetic fields. This energy may be transferred through conductors or space and may be converted to other forms of energy.

A380D3D6327441299CA217ED186D5E22.description: Power* is the time-rate at which work is done or energy is expended.

350C2B4BEB034E01AA0F836A7F2279E2.description: Work done against friction results in an increase in the internal energy of the system.

AA4B224E2079442ABDE8F153B07C3EBD.description: When work* is done on or by a system, there is a change in the total energy* of the system.

A7247A0C74D64FD5B15093BBD70A601D.description: In a nonideal mechanical system, as mechanical energy decreases there is a corresponding increase in other energies such as internal energy.*

C182EB63D8A64C3DB4F6473BF4F78027.description: In an ideal mechanical system, the sum of the macroscopic kinetic and potential energies (mechanical energy) is constant.*

7EB075D583BC45F8BEDC9D2C78BC2407.description: Kinetic energy* is the energy an object possesses by virtue of its motion.

AD861E966DED4BFAB438CED2B65D5C1E.description: Potential energy is the energy an object possesses by virtue of its position or condition. Types of potential energy include gravitational* and elastic*.

51BCBCC8CE7A4249909F11D0CAB004C6.description: Energy may be converted among mechanical, electromagnetic, nuclear, and thermal forms.

6A1832F713C8442897590EF808157DA6.description: All energy transfers are governed by the law of conservation of energy.

FA5EC872F93A4F4CB3453E55816241B9.description: Performance Indicator 4.1: Students can observe and describe transmission of various forms of energy.

AF948198115A4B86AE0CC02E580F90E5.description:
Standard 4: The Physical Setting (Students will understand and apply scientific concepts, principles, and theories pertaining to the physical setting
and living environment and recognize the historical development of ideas in science.)

Key Idea 2: Solving interdisciplinary problems involves a variety of skills and strategies, including
effective work habits; gathering and processing information; generating and analyzing
ideas; realizing ideas; making connections among the common themes of mathematics,
science, and technology; and presenting results.

• If students participate in an extended, culminating mathematics, science, and
technology project, then students should:

§ work effectively

§ gather and process information

§ generate and analyze ideas

§ observe common themes

§ realize ideas

§ present results

6390DD676ACA41BD89B8C438AECAC2F7.description:
Key Idea 1: The knowledge and skills of mathematics, science, and technology are used together to make informed decisions and solve problems, especially those relating to issues of science/technology/society, consumer decision making, design, and inquiry into phenomena.
• address real-world problems, using scientific methodology

ADDB586FFB8C4BD0A05A783497E0B720.description:
Standard 7: Interdisciplinary Problem Solving (Students will apply the knowledge and thinking skills of mathematics, science, and technology to address real-life
problems and make informed decisions.)

9CF4AC71905744409E4542CAA4043328.description:
Key Idea 6: In order to arrive at the best solution that meets criteria within constraints, it is often necessary to make trade-offs.
• determine optimal solutions to problems that can be solved using quantitative
methods

3998D88D34714A3CAA8F42148C4E3D38.description: Search for multiple trends when analyzing data for patterns, and identify data that do not fit the trends. • deduce patterns from the organization and presentation of data • identify and develop models, using patterns in data

4A33316E033842228BB71D125679F1B7.description:
Use sophisticated mathematical models, such as graphs and equations of various
algebraic or trigonometric functions.
• predict the behavior of physical systems, using mathematical models such as
graphs and equations

6A7A20D5D45442D4B9D5D93252DC6F39.description: Key Idea 5: Identifying patterns of change is necessary for making predictions about future behavior and conditions.

05EC54D670694741926DA2C6103CE0AC.description: Cite specific examples of how dynamic equilibrium is achieved by equality of change in opposing directions.

35E0667BD1F443EDA5E38BDE249B755E.description: Describe specific instances of how disturbances might affect a system’s equilibrium, from small disturbances that do not upset the equilibrium to larger disturbances (threshold level) that cause the system to become unstable.

169B7394876647C0976AD37EBCDEB224.description:
Key Idea 4:
Equilibrium is a state of stability due either to a lack of change (static equilibrium) or a
balance between opposing forces (dynamic equilibrium).

22A828D83ABD4EC792E4D99418B3D562.description:
Extend their use of powers of ten notation to understanding the exponential
function and performing operations with exponential factors.
• estimate quantitative results, using orders of magnitude
• simplify calculations by using scientific notation

BE648088827E446FABFF634B3763FFB6.description:
Describe the effects of changes in scale on the functioning of physical, biological, or
designed systems.

610F8C432F4A41FB94EEB9201C6ED74C.description:
Key Idea 3: The grouping of magnitudes of size, time, frequency, and pressures or other units of measurement into a series of relative order provides a useful way to deal with the
immense range and the changes in scale that affect the behavior and design of systems.

BDAE2F9F50274596B539FDE61CCAD739.description: Compare predictions to actual observations, using test models. • validate or reject a model based on collated experimental data • predict the behavior of a system, using a model

212A86041C9D40558BE6BE7430E42A6D.description: Find and use mathematical models that behave in the same manner as the processes under investigation. • represent the behavior of real-world systems, using physical and mathematical models

1EC74ACD0D3C4CA4A1C17199968940F9.description:
Collect information about the behavior of a system and use modeling tools to
represent the operation of the system.
• use observations of the behavior of a system to develop a model

8C583EEE69554AAAAD1976BF52F21A00.description:
Revise a model to create a more complete or improved representation of the
system.

21107D8971F14C02B61E10D29D0FF8C1.description: Key Idea 2: Models are simplified representations of objects, structures, or systems used in analysis, explanation, interpretation, or design.

3511945512174CF081DEF71F1262EEC5.description: Define boundary conditions when doing systems analysis to determine what SYSTEMS influences a system and how it behaves.

35AD92D12DAC426CA2D2736232FCEF31.description: Key Idea 1: Through systems thinking, people can recognize the commonalities that exist among all systems and how parts of a system interrelate and combine to perform specific functions.

A9C96D28FF0540E8AA4C2DAEB52FB935.description:
Standard 6 - Interconnectedness: Common Themes (Students will understand the relationships and common themes that connect mathematics, science, and technology
and apply the themes to these and other areas of learning.)

3EF028E964A640438413CD7AD6ACDFDB.description: Key Idea 3: Information technology can have positive and negative impacts on society, depending upon how it is used.

0D52D2B18B604D45A61DF5131C5C0797.description: Key Idea 2: Knowledge of the impacts and limitations of information systems is essential to its effective and ethical use.

E6E953E96F89488A8DD7570382CADDBF.description:
Model solutions to a range of problems in mathematics, science, and technology, using computer simulation software.
• use software to model and extend classroom and laboratory experiences, recognizing the differences between the model used for understanding and realworld behavior

6671C30F5EA446D2856597CDB57418FA.description: Utilize electronic networks to share information.

FE378E71328F4E18AA47B60FD887C6F8.description:
Access, select, collate, and analyze information obtained from a wide range of sources such as research databases, foundations, organizations, national libraries, and electronic communication networks, including the Internet.
• use knowledge of physics to evaluate articles in the popular press on contemporary scientific topics

AD1AD5079C6141E8AFB2B373633B467D.description:

etc.)

e.g., literature review, electronic resources, library research
• use appropriate technology to gather experimental data, develop models, and present results

A5B5838697774DE2A5263FD58CC75A47.description:
Understand and use the more advanced features of word processing, spreadsheets,
and database software.

C82B778B9AA14F8A8516EABEB1985609.description: Key Idea 1: Information technology is used to retrieve, process, and communicate information as a tool to enhance learning.

A105CC6D30524E67BF53E82ED34EDD40.description: Standard 2 (Students will access, generate, process, and transfer information, using appropriate technologies.)

7D89EE1A95384851AE5F788953FF32F3.description:
Students engage in the following steps of a design process: 
-initiate and carry out a thorough investigation of an unfamiliar situation and identify needs and opportunities for technological invention or innovation
-identify, locate, and use a wide range of information resources, and document through notes and sketches how findings relate to the problem 
-generate creative solutions, break ideas into significant functional elements, and explore possible refinements; predict possible outcomes, using mathematical and functional modeling techniques; choose the optimal solution to the problem, clearly documenting ideas against design criteria and constraints; and explain how human understandings, economics, ergonomics, and environmental considerations have influenced the solution
-develop work schedules and working plans which include optimal use and cost of materials, processes, time, and expertise; construct a model of the solution, incorporating developmental modifications while working to a high degree of quality (craftsmanship) 
-devise a test of the solution according to the design criteria and perform the test; record, portray, and logically evaluate performance test results through quantitative, graphic, and verbal means. Use a variety of creative verbal and graphic techniques effectively and persuasively to present conclusions, predict impacts and new problems, and suggest and pursue modifications

091CA215FF0C4A65B57AB2DC92EE40F6.description: Key Idea 1: Engineering design is an iterative process involving modeling and optimization (finding and Design the best solution within given constraints) which is used to develop technological solutions to problems within given constraints. (Note: The design process could apply to activities from simple investigations to long-term projects.)

6343392B8D444A82B5CA3CE0A61ABB90.description:
Based on the results of the test and through public discussion, revise the
explanation and contemplate additional research. (Note: Public discussion may
include lab partners, lab groups, classes, etc.)

342274614DDC4FC9B585A4B70D17BBB8.description:
Assess correspondence between the predicted result contained in the hypothesis
and the actual result, and reach a conclusion as to whether or not the explanation
on which the prediction was based is supported.

BB4090A15837406080DF333D2BC80630.description:
Apply statistical analysis techniques when appropriate to test if chance alone
explains the result.
• examine collected data to evaluate the reliability of experimental results, including percent error, range, standard deviation, line of best fit, and the use of the
correct number of significant digits

0C80D5F5197944F097357EB72CD658A1.description:
Use various means of representing and organizing observations (e.g., diagrams,
tables, charts, graphs, and equations) and insightfully interpret the organized data.
• use appropriate methods to present scientific information (e.g., lab reports,
posters, research papers, or multimedia presentations)
• identify possible sources of error in data collection and explain their effects on
experimental results

F0F5863C196746CABBF1343F84AAF199.description: Key Idea 3: The observations made while testing proposed explanations, when analyzed using conventional and invented methods, provide new insights into phenomena.

8CBB3084C8C445718B0E5B0B3A161E07.description:
Carry out a research plan for testing explanations, including selecting and developing techniques, acquiring and building apparatus, and recording observations as necessary. (Note: This could apply to many activities from simple investigations to
long-term projects.)

CA69D850A92B4CDA981EA272CFA0DF5E.description:
Develop and present proposals including formal hypotheses to test explanations; i.e.,
predict what should be observed under specific conditions if the explanation is true.

B4049D1FB9C64B94B9BD59B5FB689189.description: Refine research ideas through library investigations, including electronic information retrieval and reviews of the literature, and through peer feedback obtained from review and discussion.

5623098948E24E3DA300AA0D186322A4.description:
Devise ways of making observations to test proposed explanations.
• design an experiment to investigate the relationship between physical
phenomena

FD86B6671AB643EEAA88EAB99F34F187.description:
Key Idea 2: Beyond the use of reasoning and consensus, scientific inquiry involves the testing of
proposed explanations involving the use of conventional techniques and procedures
and usually requiring considerable ingenuity.

839DF9DEB7364AE0BC71F4EDD5558860.description:
Key Idea 1: The central purpose of scientific inquiry is to develop explanations of natural phenomena in a continuing, creative process.
• develop extended visual models and mathematical formulations to represent an
understanding of natural phenomena
• clarify ideas through reasoning, research, and discussion
• evaluate competing explanations and overcome misconceptions

B39FC1AB1B174A10B2EAF84666E81EBB.description:
Key Idea 3:
Critical thinking skills are used in the solution of mathematical problems.
M3.1 Apply algebraic and geometric concepts and skills to the solution of problems.
• explain the physical relevance of properties of a graphical representation of realworld data, e.g., slope, intercepts, area under the curve

5B73755110EE4B24A62783ACF581C4CA.description:

M2.1 Use deductive reasoning to construct and evaluate conjectures and arguments, recognizing that patterns and relationships in mathematics assist them in arriving at these
conjectures and arguments.
• interpret graphs to determine the mathematical relationship between the
variables

C0456C3FA95B46989610DF76B3B7F9D6.description:
Key Idea 1: Abstraction and symbolic representation are used to communicate mathematically.
M1.1 Use algebraic and geometric representations to describe and compare data.
• use scaled diagrams to represent and manipulate vector quantities
• represent physical quantities in graphical form
• construct graphs of real-world data (scatter plots, line or curve of best fit)
• manipulate equations to solve for unknowns
• use dimensional analysis to confirm algebraic solutions

3D7E7D03287F432D99639DEA8BC372F4.description:
Standard 1 - Analysis, Inquiry, and Design. (Students will use mathematical analysis, scientific inquiry, and engineering design, as
and appropriate, to pose questions, seek answers, and develop solutions.)
